<!-- ═══════════════ LESSON 1-1 ═══════════════ -->
<div class="lesson" id="lesson-1-1">
  <div class="lesson-header">
    <div class="lesson-eyebrow">Chapter 1 · The Basics · Lesson 1</div>
    <h2 class="lesson-title">What happens when you tap your card?</h2>
    <p class="lesson-lead">You tap your card and the screen says "Approved" in under two seconds. But in those two seconds, your card information has crossed the globe and come back. Here's the story.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>It all starts with a question</h3>
  <p>The moment your card touches the reader, the payment terminal sends a message — a question — to your bank: <strong>"This person wants to spend £49.99 at this shop. Do you allow it?"</strong></p>
  <p>Your bank has to answer that question, fast. If it says yes, the screen lights up green. If it says no, you get the embarrassing "Declined" message.</p>

  <div class="box story">
    <span class="box-icon">☕</span>
    <div>
      <div class="box-title">Imagine it like calling directory enquiries</div>
      <div class="box-text">The shop's till is like someone calling to ask if you have an account with their friend's bank. The bank checks its records, says "yes, they have the money" or "no, they don't" — and the answer comes back in the time it takes to blink.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3>The four stops the message makes</h3>
  <p>That message doesn't go directly from the shop to your bank. It passes through four different places:</p>

  <div class="flow-wrap">
    <div class="flow">
      <div class="flow-node lit">
        <span class="flow-node-icon">🛍️</span>
        <span class="flow-node-name">The shop</span>
        <span class="flow-node-role">Asks: "Can they pay?"</span>
      </div>
      <div class="flow-arrow">→<div class="flow-arrow-label">sends</div></div>
      <div class="flow-node">
        <span class="flow-node-icon">🏦</span>
        <span class="flow-node-name">Shop's bank</span>
        <span class="flow-node-role">Passes it along</span>
      </div>
      <div class="flow-arrow">→<div class="flow-arrow-label">routes</div></div>
      <div class="flow-node teal">
        <span class="flow-node-icon">🌐</span>
        <span class="flow-node-name">Visa/Mastercard</span>
        <span class="flow-node-role">Finds your bank</span>
      </div>
      <div class="flow-arrow">→<div class="flow-arrow-label">asks</div></div>
      <div class="flow-node lit">
        <span class="flow-node-icon">💳</span>
        <span class="flow-node-name">Your bank</span>
        <span class="flow-node-role">Approves or declines</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p>The answer then travels back the same way — your bank → Visa/Mastercard → shop's bank → the terminal — and the whole thing takes about 1–3 seconds.</p>

  <div class="box insight">
    <span class="box-icon">💡</span>
    <div>
      <div class="box-title">Something surprising: Visa and Mastercard don't hold any money</div>
      <div class="box-text">Visa and Mastercard are like telephone exchanges — they connect your bank to the shop's bank. They don't own your money. They just make sure the message gets to the right place, and everyone plays by the same rules.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3>What is your bank actually checking?</h3>
  <p>In those 1–3 seconds, your bank checks several things at once:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Do you have enough money or credit available?</li>
    <li>Is the card valid and not reported lost or stolen?</li>
    <li>Does this purchase look normal for you? (Buying coffee in London when you were in Paris an hour ago might raise a flag)</li>
    <li>Is the transaction within your daily spending limits?</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="quiz" id="quiz-1-1">
    <div class="quiz-tag">✏️ Quick check</div>
    <div class="quiz-question" id="qq-1-1">When you tap your card and it's approved — who makes the final decision to say yes?</div>
