<!-- ═══════════════ LESSON 1-2 ═══════════════ -->
<div class="lesson" id="lesson-1-2">
  <div class="lesson-header">
    <div class="lesson-eyebrow">Chapter 1 · The Basics · Lesson 2</div>
    <h2 class="lesson-title">The four people in every payment</h2>
    <p class="lesson-lead">Every single card payment on earth involves four different parties working together. Understanding who they are explains almost everything about how payments work.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>Meet the four players</h3>

  <table class="tbl">
    <tr><th>Who</th><th>What they do</th><th>Real-world example</th></tr>
    <tr><td>You (cardholder)</td><td>The person paying</td><td>You, buying a coffee</td></tr>
    <tr><td>The merchant</td><td>The business being paid</td><td>The coffee shop</td></tr>
    <tr><td>The acquirer</td><td>The merchant's bank — processes payments for businesses</td><td>Barclays, Worldpay, Stripe</td></tr>
    <tr><td>The issuer</td><td>Your bank — gave you the card and holds your money</td><td>HSBC, Chase, Monzo</td></tr>
  </table>

  <p>And there's a fifth player in the middle — the <strong>card scheme</strong> (Visa or Mastercard). They're the network that connects all four parties and sets the rules everyone must follow.</p>

  <div class="box story">
    <span class="box-icon">📮</span>
    <div>
      <div class="box-title">Think of it like the postal system</div>
      <div class="box-text">You want to send a letter (money) to someone in another country. You give it to your local post office (acquirer). They send it through the international postal network (Visa/Mastercard). It arrives at the recipient's local post office (issuer), who delivers it. Neither post office holds the money — they just route it.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3>Why does any of this matter?</h3>
  <p>Before card networks existed, your bank would need a direct agreement with every other bank in the world to let you pay at any shop. That's impossible. Visa and Mastercard solved this by becoming the shared highway — every bank connects to them, and the highway connects everyone together.</p>

  <div class="box insight">
    <span class="box-icon">💡</span>
    <div>
      <div class="box-title">Who actually pays the fees?</div>
      <div class="box-text">The shop pays a small percentage of every sale — typically 0.5%–2%. This gets split between the shop's bank, your bank, and Visa/Mastercard. You, the customer, pay nothing extra (in most countries). Your bank uses its share to fund things like cashback rewards and travel insurance on your card.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="quiz" id="quiz-1-2">
    <div class="quiz-tag">✏️ Quick check</div>
    <div class="quiz-question" id="qq-1-2">Your friend pays at a coffee shop with their Monzo card on a Visa network. Which of the following is the "issuer"?</div>
    <div class="quiz-opts" id="qo-1-2">
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('1-2',0,1)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">A</span>The coffee shop</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('1-2',1,1)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">B</span>Monzo — they gave your friend the card and hold their money</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('1-2',2,1)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">C</span>Visa</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('1-2',3,1)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">D</span>The coffee shop's bank</button>
    </div>
    <div class="quiz-feedback" id="qfb-1-2"></div>
    <div class="quiz-footer">
      <span class="quiz-count" id="qc-1-2"></span>
      <span class="quiz-score" id="qs-1-2"></span>
      <button class="quiz-next" id="qn-1-2" onclick="nextQ('1-2')">Next →</button>
