<!-- ═══════════════ LESSON 2-1 ═══════════════ -->
<div class="lesson" id="lesson-2-1">
  <div class="lesson-header">
    <div class="lesson-eyebrow">Chapter 2 · Your Card · Lesson 4</div>
    <h2 class="lesson-title">What those 16 numbers actually mean</h2>
    <p class="lesson-lead">The number on your card isn't random. Every digit has a purpose — and together they tell the payment network everything it needs to know to route your payment to the right bank.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>Breaking down a card number</h3>
  <p>Take a typical card number: <strong style="font-family:var(--mono);letter-spacing:.15em;color:var(--rust)">4532 0151 1283 0366</strong></p>

  <table class="tbl">
    <tr><th>Digits</th><th>What it means</th></tr>
    <tr><td>First digit: 4</td><td>The "4" tells everyone this is a Visa card. Mastercards start with 5 (or 2). Amex starts with 3.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>First 6–8 digits (453201...)</td><td>The bank code — tells the network which specific bank issued this card, so it knows where to send the approval request</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Middle digits</td><td>Your account number — unique to you within your bank</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Last digit (6)</td><td>A "check digit" — calculated from all the other digits using a formula. Catches typos when you type your card number online.</td></tr>
  </table>

  <div class="box story">
    <span class="box-icon">📮</span>
    <div>
      <div class="box-title">Like a postcode for your bank</div>
      <div class="box-text">The first 6–8 digits work like a postcode. Before the payment network reads your full address (account number), it reads the postcode (bank code) to know which sorting office (bank) to route your payment to. Without those first digits, nobody would know which of thousands of banks around the world to contact.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3>Quick guide: which number = which network?</h3>
  <table class="tbl">
    <tr><th>Starts with</th><th>Network</th><th>Digits</th></tr>
    <tr><td>4...</td><td>Visa</td><td>16</td></tr>
    <tr><td>51–55 or 22–27</td><td>Mastercard</td><td>16</td></tr>
    <tr><td>34 or 37</td><td>American Express</td><td>15</td></tr>
    <tr><td>6011 or 65</td><td>Discover</td><td>16</td></tr>
  </table>

  <div class="box insight">
    <span class="box-icon">💡</span>
    <div>
      <div class="box-title">Credit vs debit — same number, different account</div>
      <div class="box-text">Credit cards and debit cards look identical. The difference is what's behind them: a debit card takes money from your current account (money you already have), while a credit card borrows money from your bank (you pay it back later). Same 16-digit format, same chip, same network — but very different financial products.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="quiz" id="quiz-2-1">
    <div class="quiz-tag">✏️ Quick check</div>
    <div class="quiz-question" id="qq-2-1">Someone gives you their card number starting with "5412..." to take a payment. Which network will process it?</div>
