<div class="lesson" id="lesson-2-2">
  <div class="lesson-header">
    <div class="lesson-eyebrow">Chapter 2 · Your Card · Lesson 5</div>
    <h2 class="lesson-title">Chip, swipe, or tap — what's actually different?</h2>
    <p class="lesson-lead">You have three ways to use a card at a shop. They look similar, but they have very different security properties — and that's why banks keep pushing you towards chip and tap.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>The magnetic stripe (swipe) — the old way</h3>
  <p>The black stripe on the back of your card stores your card information. When you swipe, the terminal reads it like a cassette tape. The problem? It's the <strong>same data every single time</strong>. If a criminal puts a hidden skimmer on an ATM or card reader, they capture your data once — and can use it forever.</p>

  <div class="box warning">
    <span class="box-icon">⚠️</span>
    <div>
      <div class="box-title">Magnetic stripes are being phased out</div>
      <div class="box-text">Visa has stopped including magnetic stripes on new cards in Europe. The UK and EU have largely moved past swipe — but you might still use it in some countries. If you're ever asked to swipe instead of chip in a country where chips are standard, be cautious.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3>The chip (insert) — the secure way</h3>
  <p>The gold chip on your card is a tiny computer. Every time you insert it, the chip generates a <strong>unique secret code</strong> for that specific transaction. Even if someone captures that code, it's useless — it only worked for that one payment. This is what makes chip cloning essentially impossible.</p>

  <h3>Contactless (tap) — the fast way</h3>
  <p>Tapping your card (or phone, or watch) uses radio waves — the same technology as an Oyster card. Your card's chip generates the same unique-per-transaction code, but sends it wirelessly. There's a spending limit (£100 in the UK) because above that, the bank wants you to prove it's really you by entering your PIN.</p>

  <table class="tbl">
    <tr><th></th><th>Swipe</th><th>Chip & PIN</th><th>Contactless tap</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Speed</td><td>Fast</td><td>Slowest</td><td>Fastest</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Security</td><td>Low — can be copied</td><td>Very high</td><td>Very high</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Spend limit</td><td>None</td><td>None</td><td>£100 (UK)</td></tr>
    <tr><td>PIN needed</td><td>Sometimes</td><td>Always</td><td>Only over limit</td></tr>
  </table>

