<div class="lesson" id="lesson-3-1">
  <div class="lesson-header">
    <div class="lesson-eyebrow">Chapter 3 · Staying Safe Online · Lesson 7</div>
    <h2 class="lesson-title">Why online payments need extra protection</h2>
    <p class="lesson-lead">Shopping online is convenient — but there's a fundamental problem. Anyone who knows your card number can use it. Here's how the industry tries to solve that.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>The online fraud problem in plain English</h3>
  <p>When you pay in a shop, the card reader knows you're physically there with your card. You also prove it's you with your PIN. Online, there's no terminal, no PIN. Anyone who has your card number, expiry date, and CVV code can buy things pretending to be you.</p>
  <p>This is why online fraud is estimated to be about <strong>10 times more common</strong> than in-store fraud.</p>

  <div class="box warning">
    <span class="box-icon">⚠️</span>
    <div>
      <div class="box-title">Where do fraudsters get card details?</div>
      <div class="box-text">Data breaches at websites where you've shopped, phishing emails that trick you into entering details on a fake website, or buying stolen card data on underground forums. Once they have your details, they shop online until your bank blocks them.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3>The solution: ask for more proof it's really you</h3>
  <p>Banks and card networks introduced an extra security step for online payments called <strong>3-D Secure</strong> (often just called "3DS"). When you shop online, the website quietly asks your bank: "Is this really your customer?" Your bank then asks you to prove it.</p>

  <div class="box story">
    <span class="box-icon">🏧</span>
    <div>
      <div class="box-title">Like being asked for ID at a bar</div>
      <div class="box-text">A barman can see you're physically present, but they still ask for ID to confirm you're who you say you are. 3-D Secure is the online equivalent — even though your card number arrived digitally, your bank checks you're actually the person behind it.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="box insight">
    <span class="box-icon">💡</span>
    <div>
      <div class="box-title">In Europe this is the law</div>
      <div class="box-text">EU and UK regulations (called PSD2) require banks to apply Strong Customer Authentication (SCA) to online card payments. That's why European online shopping usually involves a verification step that wasn't required a few years ago. It reduced online fraud significantly.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

