<div class="lesson" id="lesson-3-2">
  <div class="lesson-header">
    <div class="lesson-eyebrow">Chapter 3 · Staying Safe Online · Lesson 8</div>
    <h2 class="lesson-title">That verification text you receive — explained</h2>
    <p class="lesson-lead">You're paying online, everything's filled in, and suddenly a text arrives with a 6-digit code. What is that, why does it happen, and why sometimes it doesn't?</p>
  </div>

  <h3>That text is called a One-Time Password (OTP)</h3>
  <p>When your bank sends you a code via text message while you're shopping online, it's verifying that you — the real person who registered that phone number — are the one making the payment. Even if a fraudster has your card number, they don't have your phone. So receiving the code proves it's really you.</p>

  <h3>Why don't you always get a verification text?</h3>
  <p>Here's something interesting: if you've shopped on Amazon, Netflix, or other big sites, you might have noticed you almost never get asked to verify. That's not because those sites skipped security — it's because your bank's system quietly decided it was low-risk enough to approve without interrupting you.</p>

  <div class="box story">
    <span class="box-icon">🏦</span>
    <div>
      <div class="box-title">Your bank is making a silent risk decision</div>
      <div class="box-text">Behind the scenes, your bank's system scores each transaction: "Is this person's usual device? Is this a site they've bought from before? Is the amount normal for them?" If everything looks familiar and low-risk, your bank silently approves it — what's called a "frictionless" approval. You never see a popup. If something looks unusual, they send the text.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="box good">
    <span class="box-icon">✅</span>
    <div>
      <div class="box-title">Never share that verification code with anyone</div>
      <div class="box-text">Fraudsters sometimes call pretending to be your bank and ask for the OTP you just received. Your real bank will never, ever ask you to read them a code over the phone. If someone calls asking for it — hang up. They're trying to authorise a fraudulent payment in your name.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="quiz" id="quiz-3-2">
    <div class="quiz-tag">✏️ Quick check</div>
    <div class="quiz-question" id="qq-3-2">You receive a text saying "Your verification code is 483920. Never share this." Someone then calls claiming to be your bank and asks for the code. What should you do?</div>
