<!-- ═══════════════ LESSON 4-1 ═══════════════ -->
<div class="lesson" id="lesson-4-1">
  <div class="lesson-header">
    <div class="lesson-eyebrow">Chapter 4 · Fraud & Disputes · Lesson 9</div>
    <h2 class="lesson-title">How card fraud actually happens</h2>
    <p class="lesson-lead">Understanding how fraudsters operate is the best defence against becoming a victim. None of this is complicated — and once you know it, you'll spot the warning signs immediately.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>The main ways card details get stolen</h3>

  <table class="tbl">
    <tr><th>Method</th><th>How it works</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Phishing</td><td>A fake email pretending to be your bank, Amazon, or HMRC — with a link to a fake website that steals your details when you enter them</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Data breaches</td><td>A website you've shopped on gets hacked and card details are stolen from their database</td></tr>
    <tr><td>ATM skimming</td><td>A hidden device attached to an ATM that reads the magnetic stripe and cameras that capture your PIN</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Shoulder surfing</td><td>Someone watching you enter your card details or PIN in public</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Social engineering</td><td>A phone call from someone convincing you to share your details by pretending to be from your bank or a government agency</td></tr>
  </table>

  <div class="box warning">
    <span class="box-icon">⚠️</span>
    <div>
      <div class="box-title">The warning signs of a scam call</div>
      <div class="box-text">They create urgency ("your account will be closed today"), they ask you to move money to a "safe account," they ask for your PIN or a verification code, or they ask you to download an app so they can "help" you. These are all red flags. Your real bank does none of these things.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3>What happens after fraud is committed</h3>
  <p>Usually one of two things triggers discovery: you check your statement and spot a charge you don't recognise, or your bank's fraud system detects unusual activity and alerts you (or blocks the card). The moment you report it, your bank starts an investigation and will typically refund you within a few working days if the fraud is confirmed.</p>

  <div class="box good">
    <span class="box-icon">✅</span>
    <div>
      <div class="box-title">Check your statement regularly — even if you use app notifications</div>
      <div class="box-text">Many fraudsters make small test purchases first (£1–£5) to check the card works before making larger ones. These can slip through notification fatigue. A quick scroll through your statement once a week catches them early.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="quiz" id="quiz-4-1">
    <div class="quiz-tag">✏️ Quick check</div>
    <div class="quiz-question" id="qq-4-1">You get an email saying "Your Amazon account has been compromised. Click here to verify your card details immediately." What do you do?</div>
    <div class="quiz-opts" id="qo-4-1">
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('4-1',0,2)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">A</span>Click the link and enter your details quickly before the account is closed</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('4-1',1,2)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">B</span>Forward it to a friend and ask if they think it's real</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('4-1',2,2)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">C</span>Do not click the link. Open Amazon directly in your browser by typing the address, and check if there's actually an issue.</span></button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('4-1',3,2)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">D</span>Reply to the email asking for more information</button>
    </div>
    <div class="quiz-feedback" id="qfb-4-1"></div>
