<!-- ═══════════════ LESSON 4-2 ═══════════════ -->
<div class="lesson" id="lesson-4-2">
  <div class="lesson-header">
    <div class="lesson-eyebrow">Chapter 4 · Fraud & Disputes · Lesson 10</div>
    <h2 class="lesson-title">Chargebacks — your right to get money back</h2>
    <p class="lesson-lead">If something goes wrong with a card payment — fraud, a dodgy merchant, goods that never arrived — you have a legal right to get your money back. Here's how it works.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>What is a chargeback?</h3>
  <p>A chargeback is when your bank forcibly reverses a payment on your behalf. You contact your bank, explain the problem, and if they agree it qualifies, they take the money back from the merchant's bank and return it to you. It's one of the most powerful consumer protections that comes with using a card.</p>

  <div class="box story">
    <span class="box-icon">⚖️</span>
    <div>
      <div class="box-title">Think of your bank as your advocate</div>
      <div class="box-text">When you dispute a payment, your bank fights on your behalf. They contact the merchant's bank and say "our customer says they shouldn't have been charged for this." The merchant then has a chance to prove the transaction was legitimate. If they can't, you get your money back.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3>When can you use a chargeback?</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>You were charged but the goods never arrived</li>
    <li>The goods were significantly different from what was described</li>
    <li>You were charged twice for the same thing</li>
    <li>A subscription charged you after you cancelled</li>
    <li>You didn't authorise the payment (fraud)</li>
    <li>The business closed down before fulfilling your order</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="box insight">
    <span class="box-icon">💡</span>
    <div>
      <div class="box-title">Credit cards give you extra protection: Section 75</div>
      <div class="box-text">In the UK, if you pay for something costing between £100 and £30,000 on a credit card and something goes wrong, Section 75 of the Consumer Credit Act makes your credit card provider equally liable with the merchant. This is even stronger than a chargeback and is why many people use credit cards for big purchases like holidays and electronics.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3>How to raise a chargeback</h3>
  <p>Contact your bank or card issuer directly — through their app, online banking, or by calling the number on the back of your card. Most UK banks now have chargeback claim forms in their apps. You typically have up to 120 days from the transaction to raise a dispute, but act quickly — the sooner the better.</p>

