<div class="lesson" id="lesson-5-2">
  <div class="lesson-header">
    <div class="lesson-eyebrow">Chapter 5 · The Money Trail · Lesson 12</div>
    <h2 class="lesson-title">When does the shop actually get paid?</h2>
    <p class="lesson-lead">You tap and go. The shop thinks they've been paid. But the money often doesn't arrive for a day or two — or longer. Here's why, and what it means for businesses.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>The gap between "approved" and "paid"</h3>
  <p>As we learned in Chapter 1, approval and payment are different things. For most merchants, money arrives in their bank account <strong>1–2 working days</strong> after the transaction. Big chains have negotiated faster settlement; small businesses often wait longer.</p>

  <div class="box story">
    <span class="box-icon">🛒</span>
    <div>
      <div class="box-title">A market stall on a busy Saturday</div>
      <div class="box-text">Imagine a food market trader who takes £2,000 in card payments on Saturday. They need to pay for their pitch, buy stock for next week, and pay their staff. But the £2,000 won't be in their account until Monday at the earliest — possibly Tuesday if there are bank holidays. Managing this gap is a real headache for small businesses.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3>Why some businesses get paid faster</h3>
  <p>Some payment providers offer "instant" or "same-day" settlement — but this costs extra. They're essentially lending you the money and waiting to get reimbursed from the card networks later. Large supermarkets and retailers often negotiate premium settlement terms because of their transaction volumes.</p>

  <h3>The reserve — money held back as security</h3>
  <p>New or higher-risk businesses often have part of their payments held back for weeks or months as insurance. If customers later dispute payments, the payment processor has funds available to cover it without chasing the merchant. This can be a significant strain for small businesses — they might process £10,000 in a month but only have £9,000 available because £1,000 is in reserve.</p>

