<!-- 6-2 -->
<div class="lesson" id="lesson-6-2">
  <div class="lesson-header">
    <div class="lesson-eyebrow" style="color:var(--teal)">Module 2 · Intermediate · Chapter 6 · Lesson 14</div>
    <h2 class="lesson-title">Liability shift — who pays when fraud slips through?</h2>
    <p class="lesson-lead">When fraud happens despite authentication, someone has to absorb the loss. 3DS doesn't just protect cardholders — it reallocates who's financially responsible when things go wrong.</p>
  </div>
  <h3>Before 3DS: the merchant usually loses</h3>
  <p>Without any authentication, if a criminal uses a stolen card online and the cardholder disputes the charge, the merchant typically has to refund the money — even though they did nothing wrong. This is because the merchant accepted the payment without verifying the cardholder's identity.</p>
  <h3>After 3DS: the liability shifts to the issuer</h3>
  <p>When a transaction is authenticated via 3DS — whether frictionlessly or via a challenge — and that transaction is later disputed as fraud, the <strong>liability shifts to your bank</strong>. The merchant is protected. Your bank authenticated the transaction and said "yes, this is our customer" — so if it wasn't, that's their problem to resolve.</p>
  <div class="box insight">
    <span class="box-icon">💡</span>
    <div>
      <div class="box-title">This is the primary business reason merchants implement 3DS</div>
      <div class="box-text">It's not purely altruism about security. Merchants implement 3DS largely because it shifts financial risk away from them. A merchant with high fraud rates that doesn't use 3DS is absorbing all those losses themselves. With 3DS, the bank that authenticated the transaction takes the hit.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <h3>What about when the merchant claims a 3DS exemption?</h3>
  <p>If a merchant decides to skip 3DS for a transaction (using a legitimate exemption like "low value" or "trusted merchant"), the fraud liability stays with the merchant. Exemptions are a trade-off: less friction for the customer, but the merchant retains the risk.</p>
  <table class="tbl">
    <tr><th>Scenario</th><th>Who bears fraud liability</th></tr>
    <tr><td>No 3DS attempted</td><td>Merchant</td></tr>
    <tr><td>3DS attempted but issuer declined to participate</td><td>Issuer</td></tr>
    <tr><td>3DS frictionless (issuer approved silently)</td><td>Issuer</td></tr>
    <tr><td>3DS challenge completed successfully</td><td>Issuer</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Merchant claimed exemption, skipped 3DS</td><td>Merchant</td></tr>
  </table>
  <div class="quiz" id="quiz-6-2">
    <div class="quiz-tag">✏️ Knowledge check</div>
    <div class="quiz-question" id="qq-6-2">A merchant decides not to trigger 3DS on a £25 purchase using the "low value" exemption. The transaction turns out to be fraud. Who absorbs the loss?</div>
    <div class="quiz-opts" id="qo-6-2">
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('6-2',0,0)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">A</span>The merchant — they chose to skip authentication and retained the liability</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('6-2',1,0)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">B</span>The issuer — the amount was low so they're automatically responsible</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('6-2',2,0)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">C</span>Visa or Mastercard — they cover fraud losses on small transactions</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('6-2',3,0)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">D</span>The cardholder — they should have noticed the fraud sooner</button>
    </div>
    <div class="quiz-feedback" id="qfb-6-2"></div>
    <div class="quiz-footer"><span class="quiz-count" id="qc-6-2"></span><span class="quiz-score" id="qs-6-2"></span><button class="quiz-next" id="qn-6-2" onclick="nextQ('6-2')">Next →</button></div>
  </div>
