<!-- 6-3 -->
<div class="lesson" id="lesson-6-3">
  <div class="lesson-header">
    <div class="lesson-eyebrow" style="color:var(--teal)">Module 2 · Intermediate · Chapter 6 · Lesson 15</div>
    <h2 class="lesson-title">SCA exemptions — when businesses can skip the verification step</h2>
    <p class="lesson-lead">Requiring customers to verify every single online transaction would be exhausting. So the rules include a set of specific exemptions — situations where businesses can proceed without full authentication.</p>
  </div>
  <h3>What is SCA?</h3>
  <p>Strong Customer Authentication (SCA) is the legal requirement (under EU and UK regulations) that online card payments must be verified using at least two factors: something you <strong>know</strong> (PIN/password), something you <strong>have</strong> (your phone), or something you <strong>are</strong> (biometric). 3DS is how card payments implement SCA.</p>
  <h3>The main exemptions</h3>
  <table class="tbl">
    <tr><th>Exemption</th><th>When it applies</th><th>Who takes the liability?</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Low value</td><td>Under €30 per transaction (up to 5 in a row, or €100 cumulative)</td><td>Merchant</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Transaction Risk Analysis (TRA)</td><td>Merchant's fraud rate is below scheme thresholds — bank allows trusted merchants to skip</td><td>Whoever claimed it</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Merchant whitelisting</td><td>You've specifically told your bank to trust this merchant</td><td>Issuer</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Recurring subscription (MIT)</td><td>Regular fixed-amount charges after the first authenticated payment</td><td>Merchant</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Corporate card</td><td>B2B payments on lodge cards or virtual cards</td><td>Issuer</td></tr>
  </table>
  <div class="box story">
    <span class="box-icon">📺</span>
    <div>
      <div class="box-title">Your Netflix subscription never asks for verification — here's why</div>
      <div class="box-text">When you first subscribe, you authenticate. Every month after that, Netflix charges you using a "Merchant Initiated Transaction" (MIT) exemption — they initiated the charge, not you, based on your initial consent. They don't need to re-verify because you already agreed to recurring billing. The exemption allows it without 3DS each time.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="quiz" id="quiz-6-3">
    <div class="quiz-tag">✏️ Knowledge check</div>
    <div class="quiz-question" id="qq-6-3">A customer has successfully authenticated their first payment to a streaming service. Six months later, the service charges their card for the monthly renewal without any 3DS prompt. Is this allowed?</div>
    <div class="quiz-opts" id="qo-6-3">
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('6-3',0,0)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">A</span>Yes — recurring subscription charges qualify as MIT exemptions after the initial authenticated payment</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('6-3',1,0)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">B</span>No — SCA must be applied to every card transaction without exception</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('6-3',2,0)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">C</span>Only if the amount is under €30</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('6-3',3,0)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">D</span>Only in countries outside the EU</button>
    </div>
    <div class="quiz-feedback" id="qfb-6-3"></div>
    <div class="quiz-footer"><span class="quiz-count" id="qc-6-3"></span><span class="quiz-score" id="qs-6-3"></span><button class="quiz-next" id="qn-6-3" onclick="nextQ('6-3')">Next →</button></div>
