<!-- 7-1 -->
<div class="lesson" id="lesson-7-1">
  <div class="lesson-header">
    <div class="lesson-eyebrow" style="color:var(--teal)">Module 2 · Intermediate · Chapter 7 · Lesson 16</div>
    <h2 class="lesson-title">Why Apple Pay doesn't send your actual card number</h2>
    <p class="lesson-lead">When you pay with Apple Pay or Google Pay, your real card number never leaves your phone. Instead, a substitute number is used — and this substitution is more powerful than it sounds.</p>
  </div>
  <h3>The problem with sending real card numbers</h3>
  <p>Every time you use a card, the merchant's systems see your card number. If any merchant is hacked, your card number could be stolen. The more places your card number exists, the more places it can leak. Traditional card payments are fundamentally based on a secret (your card number) that gets shared with dozens of parties.</p>
  <h3>Tokenisation: replace the secret with a stand-in</h3>
  <p>When you add your card to Apple Pay, your bank generates a <strong>Device Primary Account Number (DPAN)</strong> — a substitute card number that's only valid for payments from your specific device. Your real card number (called the PAN or Funding PAN) stays at your bank. Nobody else ever sees it again.</p>
  <div class="flow-wrap">
    <div class="flow">
      <div class="flow-node lit"><span class="flow-node-icon">📱</span><span class="flow-node-name">Your iPhone</span><span class="flow-node-role">Sends: DPAN token</span></div>
      <div class="flow-arrow">→<div class="flow-arrow-label">instead of real PAN</div></div>
      <div class="flow-node"><span class="flow-node-icon">🏪</span><span class="flow-node-name">Merchant</span><span class="flow-node-role">Sees: token only</span></div>
      <div class="flow-arrow">→</div>
      <div class="flow-node teal"><span class="flow-node-icon">🌐</span><span class="flow-node-name">Visa/Mastercard</span><span class="flow-node-role">Detokenises to real PAN</span></div>
      <div class="flow-arrow">→</div>
      <div class="flow-node lit"><span class="flow-node-icon">🏦</span><span class="flow-node-name">Your bank</span><span class="flow-node-role">Approves/declines</span></div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="box insight">
    <span class="box-icon">💡</span>
    <div>
      <div class="box-title">Two layers of protection in every tap-to-pay</div>
      <div class="box-text">When you tap your phone to pay, two security technologies work together: (1) the token — your real card number isn't transmitted, so merchant data breaches can't expose it; and (2) a unique cryptogram — just like a chip card, the phone generates a one-time code for each transaction, so even the token can't be replayed by an attacker.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="quiz" id="quiz-7-1">
    <div class="quiz-tag">✏️ Knowledge check</div>
    <div class="quiz-question" id="qq-7-1">A retailer's payment database is hacked and millions of tokenised card numbers are stolen. Why is this less damaging than if real card numbers had been stolen?</div>
    <div class="quiz-opts" id="qo-7-1">
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('7-1',0,2)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">A</span>Tokens are encrypted, real card numbers are not</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('7-1',1,2)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">B</span>The government insures against token theft but not card number theft</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('7-1',2,2)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">C</span>Tokens only work on that specific device with a unique cryptogram — stolen tokens can't be used for fraudulent purchases without the device</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('7-1',3,2)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">D</span>Tokens automatically expire after 24 hours</button>
    </div>
    <div class="quiz-feedback" id="qfb-7-1"></div>
    <div class="quiz-footer"><span class="quiz-count" id="qc-7-1"></span><span class="quiz-score" id="qs-7-1"></span><button class="quiz-next" id="qn-7-1" onclick="nextQ('7-1')">Next →</button></div>
