<!-- 7-2 -->
<div class="lesson" id="lesson-7-2">
  <div class="lesson-header">
    <div class="lesson-eyebrow" style="color:var(--teal)">Module 2 · Intermediate · Chapter 7 · Lesson 17</div>
    <h2 class="lesson-title">How your card gets into your digital wallet</h2>
    <p class="lesson-lead">Adding a card to Apple Pay or Google Pay looks like snapping a photo. Behind that simple action is a complex multi-party security process. Here's what actually happens.</p>
  </div>
  <h3>The provisioning process</h3>
  <p>When you add your card, six parties are involved in a secure handshake that takes about 3–10 seconds:</p>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>You</strong> photograph your card or enter the number in the wallet app</li>
    <li><strong>Apple/Google</strong> (the wallet provider) sends your card details to the Token Service Provider</li>
    <li><strong>The Token Service Provider</strong> (Visa's VTS or Mastercard's MDES) looks up which bank issued your card</li>
    <li><strong>Your bank</strong> is asked whether to approve adding this card to this wallet</li>
    <li><strong>Identity verification</strong> happens — your bank asks you to prove it's you (text code, banking app confirmation, or calling their number)</li>
    <li>Once verified, your bank approves and the <strong>DPAN token</strong> is generated and stored securely in your phone's chip</li>
  </ol>
  <div class="box insight">
    <span class="box-icon">💡</span>
    <div>
      <div class="box-title">Each wallet app gets its own TRID</div>
      <div class="box-text">Apple Pay, Google Pay, and Samsung Pay each have a unique identifier called a Token Requestor ID (TRID). Your bank knows exactly which wallet your payment came from. Apple Pay has TRID 40010030273. This lets banks apply different rules per wallet — for example, requiring extra verification for a new wallet type they don't recognise yet.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="quiz" id="quiz-7-2">
    <div class="quiz-tag">✏️ Knowledge check</div>
    <div class="quiz-question" id="qq-7-2">When you add a card to Apple Pay and your bank sends you a verification text, what is your bank actually approving?</div>
    <div class="quiz-opts" id="qo-7-2">
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('7-2',0,1)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">A</span>A payment you're trying to make right now</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('7-2',1,1)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">B</span>The creation and storage of a token (DPAN) linked to your card, on your specific device</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('7-2',2,1)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">C</span>Access to your full account for Apple to manage</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('7-2',3,1)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">D</span>A change to your contactless spending limit</button>
    </div>
    <div class="quiz-feedback" id="qfb-7-2"></div>
    <div class="quiz-footer"><span class="quiz-count" id="qc-7-2"></span><span class="quiz-score" id="qs-7-2"></span><button class="quiz-next" id="qn-7-2" onclick="nextQ('7-2')">Next →</button></div>
