<!-- 8-1 -->
<div class="lesson" id="lesson-8-1">
  <div class="lesson-header">
    <div class="lesson-eyebrow" style="color:var(--teal)">Module 2 · Intermediate · Chapter 8 · Lesson 18</div>
    <h2 class="lesson-title">How banks score every transaction for risk</h2>
    <p class="lesson-lead">Every single card transaction gets a risk score in real time, often before the authorisation is even sent to your bank. Here's what goes into that score.</p>
  </div>
  <h3>Risk scoring happens in milliseconds</h3>
  <p>Modern fraud detection systems evaluate dozens of signals simultaneously and generate a risk score — typically 0 to 100 — for each transaction. The score influences whether the bank approves, declines, or steps up to 3DS challenge. All of this happens in the same 1–3 seconds as the authorisation itself.</p>
  <h3>The signals that matter most</h3>
  <table class="tbl">
    <tr><th>Signal category</th><th>What's being assessed</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Device fingerprint</td><td>Is this the same phone/browser the customer always uses? Has it been seen before?</td></tr>
    <tr><td>IP address</td><td>Is it a known VPN or proxy? Does the location match the billing address? Is it a residential IP or a data centre?</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Behavioural pattern</td><td>How fast did they type the card number? Did they paste it (bots do this)? Did they visit the site before or go straight to checkout?</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Transaction history</td><td>Does this merchant, amount, and time pattern match this cardholder's history?</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Velocity</td><td>How many recent transactions on this card/device/IP? Sudden spike = red flag.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Merchant risk</td><td>What category of merchant is this? High-fraud categories (digital goods, gambling) get scored differently.</td></tr>
  </table>
  <div class="box story">
    <span class="box-icon">🎯</span>
    <div>
      <div class="box-title">Why a score of 40 might mean very different things</div>
      <div class="box-text">A risk score of 40 on a £10 pizza order is nothing. A risk score of 40 on a £3,000 electronics purchase might trigger a challenge. Fraud systems don't just use the score alone — they combine it with the transaction amount, merchant type, and the bank's current fraud tolerance to make the final call.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="quiz" id="quiz-8-1">
    <div class="quiz-tag">✏️ Knowledge check</div>
    <div class="quiz-question" id="qq-8-1">A fraudster buys stolen card details and uses them from a VPN on a brand-new device to make a large purchase at a digital goods site. Which risk signals would this trigger?</div>
    <div class="quiz-opts" id="qo-8-1">
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('8-1',0,2)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">A</span>None — the payment details are real so it would appear legitimate</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('8-1',1,2)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">B</span>Only the large amount — amount is the only risk signal banks use</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('8-1',2,2)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">C</span>Multiple: unrecognised device, VPN IP address, high-risk merchant category, large amount, no purchase history — all raise the score significantly</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('8-1',3,2)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">D</span>The VPN signal only — banks can only see IP address data</button>
    </div>
    <div class="quiz-feedback" id="qfb-8-1"></div>
    <div class="quiz-footer"><span class="quiz-count" id="qc-8-1"></span><span class="quiz-score" id="qs-8-1"></span><button class="quiz-next" id="qn-8-1" onclick="nextQ('8-1')">Next →</button></div>
  </div>
