<!-- 9-1 -->
<div class="lesson" id="lesson-9-1">
  <div class="lesson-header">
    <div class="lesson-eyebrow" style="color:var(--teal)">Module 2 · Intermediate · Chapter 9 · Lesson 20</div>
    <h2 class="lesson-title">Inside a chargeback — what actually happens step by step</h2>
    <p class="lesson-lead">We covered chargebacks as a consumer right in the beginner module. Now let's look at the mechanics — what happens at each stage when a dispute is raised.</p>
  </div>
  <h3>The chargeback lifecycle</h3>
  <table class="tbl">
    <tr><th>Stage</th><th>Timing</th><th>What happens</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Dispute raised</td><td>Day 0</td><td>Cardholder contacts their bank claiming a problem with a transaction. Bank investigates and may issue a provisional credit to the cardholder immediately.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Chargeback filed</td><td>Day 1–30</td><td>Issuer formally files a chargeback with the scheme. The merchant's bank (acquirer) is notified and debits the merchant's account for the disputed amount plus a chargeback fee (typically £15–£35).</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Merchant notified</td><td>Day 5–45</td><td>The merchant receives the chargeback notification with a reason code. They have a limited window (typically 20–45 days) to respond with evidence.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Representment</td><td>Day 20–75</td><td>If the merchant has compelling evidence, they "represent" the transaction — submitting proof to challenge the chargeback.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Second chargeback</td><td>Day 45–120</td><td>If the issuer isn't satisfied with the merchant's evidence, they may file a second chargeback (pre-arbitration).</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Arbitration</td><td>Day 75–180</td><td>Either party escalates to the card scheme for a binding ruling. The loser pays scheme arbitration fees (Visa: ~$500, Mastercard: ~$250).</td></tr>
  </table>
  <div class="box insight">
    <span class="box-icon">💡</span>
    <div>
      <div class="box-title">Merchants absorb multiple costs per chargeback</div>
      <div class="box-text">A single chargeback doesn't just cost the transaction amount. The merchant loses: the sale amount, the goods/service already delivered, the processing fees they already paid, the chargeback fee from their acquirer, and staff time managing the dispute. For a £50 transaction, the real cost to a merchant can be £100+.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="quiz" id="quiz-9-1">
    <div class="quiz-tag">✏️ Knowledge check</div>
    <div class="quiz-question" id="qq-9-1">A merchant receives a chargeback notification and decides not to respond within the deadline. What happens?</div>
    <div class="quiz-opts" id="qo-9-1">
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('9-1',0,2)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">A</span>The chargeback is automatically cancelled — merchants don't have to respond</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('9-1',1,2)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">B</span>The scheme investigates on the merchant's behalf</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('9-1',2,2)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">C</span>The chargeback is accepted by default — the cardholder wins and the merchant absorbs the full loss</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('9-1',3,2)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">D</span>The merchant has 6 months to respond with no penalty</button>
    </div>
    <div class="quiz-feedback" id="qfb-9-1"></div>
    <div class="quiz-footer"><span class="quiz-count" id="qc-9-1"></span><span class="quiz-score" id="qs-9-1"></span><button class="quiz-next" id="qn-9-1" onclick="nextQ('9-1')">Next →</button></div>
