<!-- 9-2 -->
<div class="lesson" id="lesson-9-2">
  <div class="lesson-header">
    <div class="lesson-eyebrow" style="color:var(--teal)">Module 2 · Intermediate · Chapter 9 · Lesson 21</div>
    <h2 class="lesson-title">Reason codes — why each chargeback gets a category</h2>
    <p class="lesson-lead">Every chargeback has a reason code — a standardised label explaining why the cardholder disputed. The code determines what evidence the merchant needs to provide and whether they have a realistic chance of winning.</p>
  </div>
  <h3>Why reason codes matter</h3>
  <p>Reason codes determine the type of dispute and the rules that govern it. A fraud-related dispute plays out differently to a "goods not received" dispute. Merchants need to know which code they're dealing with before they can respond effectively.</p>
  <h3>Visa reason codes</h3>
  <table class="tbl">
    <tr><th>Code</th><th>Category</th><th>Common cause</th></tr>
    <tr><td>10.4</td><td>Card-absent fraud</td><td>CNP transaction — cardholder says they didn't make it. Most common code.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>10.5</td><td>Visa fraud monitoring</td><td>Merchant flagged by Visa's fraud programme</td></tr>
    <tr><td>12.6</td><td>Duplicate processing</td><td>Same transaction charged twice</td></tr>
    <tr><td>13.1</td><td>Merchandise not received</td><td>Goods ordered but never arrived</td></tr>
    <tr><td>13.3</td><td>Not as described</td><td>Goods significantly different from what was advertised</td></tr>
    <tr><td>13.7</td><td>Cancelled recurring</td><td>Customer cancelled subscription but was still charged</td></tr>
  </table>
  <h3>Mastercard reason codes</h3>
  <table class="tbl">
    <tr><th>Code</th><th>Category</th></tr>
    <tr><td>4853</td><td>Cardholder dispute — goods not received, not as described, or cancelled subscription</td></tr>
    <tr><td>4863</td><td>Cardholder does not recognise the transaction</td></tr>
    <tr><td>4870</td><td>Chip liability shift — merchant didn't use chip terminal</td></tr>
    <tr><td>4871</td><td>Chip/PIN liability shift — PIN not collected</td></tr>
  </table>
  <div class="box story">
    <span class="box-icon">⚖️</span>
    <div>
      <div class="box-title">Allocation vs Collaboration (Visa)</div>
      <div class="box-text">Visa splits disputes into two workflows. <strong>Allocation</strong> (fraud/auth codes like 10.4) means liability is assigned automatically based on whether 3DS was used — no merchant evidence needed, you either have liability shift or you don't. <strong>Collaboration</strong> (service codes like 13.1, 13.3) requires the merchant to actively provide evidence — delivery proof, terms agreement, communication records.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="quiz" id="quiz-9-2">
    <div class="quiz-tag">✏️ Knowledge check</div>
    <div class="quiz-question" id="qq-9-2">A merchant receives a Visa 10.4 chargeback. They authenticated the transaction with 3DS. What is likely to happen?</div>
    <div class="quiz-opts" id="qo-9-2">
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('9-2',0,0)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">A</span>The liability shifts to the issuer — the merchant wins because 3DS authentication was completed</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('9-2',1,0)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">B</span>The merchant must still provide delivery proof regardless of 3DS</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('9-2',2,0)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">C</span>The merchant has to pay arbitration fees immediately</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('9-2',3,0)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">D</span>10.4 chargebacks cannot be disputed</button>
