<!-- 10-1 -->
<div class="lesson" id="lesson-10-1">
  <div class="lesson-header">
    <div class="lesson-eyebrow" style="color:var(--teal)">Module 2 · Intermediate · Chapter 10 · Lesson 22</div>
    <h2 class="lesson-title">Interchange economics — who sets the rates and why?</h2>
    <p class="lesson-lead">Interchange is the largest single fee in every card transaction. It's set by Visa and Mastercard, paid from acquirer to issuer, and it funds almost everything cardholders get for "free." Here's how the economics actually work.</p>
  </div>
  <h3>What determines interchange rates?</h3>
  <p>Interchange isn't a single number — it's a matrix of hundreds of rates, varying by card type, transaction method, merchant category, and geography. Visa and Mastercard publish their interchange tables (they're publicly available), but they're complex.</p>
  <table class="tbl">
    <tr><th>Factor</th><th>Effect on interchange</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Debit vs credit</td><td>Debit cards: lower (typically 0.2%). Credit cards: higher (0.3%–1.5%+)</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Rewards card tier</td><td>Standard → Gold → Platinum → Infinite: each tier higher interchange to fund rewards</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Card present vs not present</td><td>Card present (chip/tap): lower. CNP (online): higher — reflects fraud risk</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Merchant category</td><td>Supermarkets & utilities: lower rates. Luxury goods & travel: higher</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Transaction size</td><td>Some categories have fixed-fee components that make small transactions proportionally expensive</td></tr>
    <tr><td>EU/UK regulation</td><td>EU caps: 0.2% debit, 0.3% credit for consumer cards within EEA. UK has similar post-Brexit caps.</td></tr>
  </table>
  <div class="box insight">
    <span class="box-icon">💡</span>
    <div>
      <div class="box-title">Interchange regulation and what changed after Brexit</div>
      <div class="box-text">EU regulations cap interchange for consumer cards within the EEA at 0.2% (debit) and 0.3% (credit). After Brexit, UK-issued cards used in the EU (and EU cards used in the UK for online purchases) can attract much higher interchange — sometimes 1.5%+. This is why some UK merchants saw significantly higher fees after Brexit for EU customer payments.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="quiz" id="quiz-10-1">
    <div class="quiz-tag">✏️ Knowledge check</div>
    <div class="quiz-question" id="qq-10-1">A restaurant owner notices their card fees are higher when customers pay with premium travel credit cards versus basic debit cards. Why?</div>
