<!-- 10-2 -->
<div class="lesson" id="lesson-10-2">
  <div class="lesson-header">
    <div class="lesson-eyebrow" style="color:var(--teal)">Module 2 · Intermediate · Chapter 10 · Lesson 23</div>
    <h2 class="lesson-title">PCI DSS — the security standard every card-accepting business must follow</h2>
    <p class="lesson-lead">PCI DSS is not a law — but ignoring it carries fines, lost card acceptance rights, and reputational damage. Here's what it actually requires.</p>
  </div>
  <h3>What is PCI DSS?</h3>
  <p>The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) is a set of security requirements created by Visa, Mastercard, and other card schemes. Any business that stores, processes, or transmits cardholder data must comply. The current version is v4.0.1 (June 2024).</p>
  <h3>The 12 requirements in plain English</h3>
  <table class="tbl">
    <tr><th>#</th><th>Requirement</th><th>What it means in practice</th></tr>
    <tr><td>1</td><td>Network security controls</td><td>Firewalls between your systems and the internet; segment the systems that touch card data</td></tr>
    <tr><td>2</td><td>Secure configurations</td><td>Change default passwords; disable unused services; harden every system</td></tr>
    <tr><td>3</td><td>Protect stored account data</td><td>Never store CVV/CVV2. Encrypt card numbers if stored. Delete data you no longer need.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>4</td><td>Encrypt data in transit</td><td>TLS 1.2+ for all card data transmissions. No unencrypted card data over any network.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>5–6</td><td>Protect against malware & vulnerabilities</td><td>Anti-malware, patch systems promptly, secure your software development process</td></tr>
    <tr><td>7–8</td><td>Restrict access</td><td>Need-to-know access only; unique IDs for everyone; MFA for all admin access</td></tr>
    <tr><td>9</td><td>Restrict physical access</td><td>Physical card data areas locked; tamper-evident seals on terminals</td></tr>
    <tr><td>10–11</td><td>Log, monitor & test</td><td>Audit logs of all access; regular vulnerability scans and penetration tests</td></tr>
    <tr><td>12</td><td>Security policy</td><td>Written policies; annual risk assessments; security awareness training</td></tr>
  </table>
  <div class="box good">
    <span class="box-icon">✅</span>
    <div>
      <div class="box-title">The easiest way to reduce PCI scope: use hosted payment pages</div>
      <div class="box-text">If card numbers never touch your servers — because payment is handled in an iframe or redirect hosted by your payment provider — your PCI obligations shrink dramatically. Instead of hundreds of controls, you might only need to complete a short self-assessment (SAQ A). This is why most e-commerce businesses use Stripe, Adyen, or similar rather than building their own card input forms.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="quiz" id="quiz-10-2">
    <div class="quiz-tag">✏️ Knowledge check</div>
    <div class="quiz-question" id="qq-10-2">A small online shop uses Stripe's hosted payment form — customers enter card details on Stripe's page, not the shop's website. What is their PCI DSS obligation?</div>
    <div class="quiz-opts" id="qo-10-2">
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('10-2',0,1)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">A</span>Full PCI DSS compliance with all 12 requirements and an on-site audit</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('10-2',1,1)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">B</span>Minimal — they complete a short self-assessment questionnaire (SAQ A) since card data never touches their servers</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('10-2',2,1)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">C</span>None — PCI DSS only applies to banks and large retailers</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('10-2',3,1)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">D</span>They must still store encrypted card numbers on their own servers</button>
    </div>
