<!-- 10-3 -->
<div class="lesson" id="lesson-10-3">
  <div class="lesson-header">
    <div class="lesson-eyebrow" style="color:var(--teal)">Module 2 · Intermediate · Chapter 10 · Lesson 24</div>
    <h2 class="lesson-title">How merchant risk is assessed and managed</h2>
    <p class="lesson-lead">Before a business can accept card payments, it must be approved by an acquirer. That approval process is a formal risk assessment — and ongoing monitoring continues long after the account is opened.</p>
  </div>
  <h3>Know Your Business (KYB)</h3>
  <p>Acquirers perform due diligence on every new merchant — known as KYB (Know Your Business). They're assessing: could this business generate fraud or chargebacks that the acquirer would have to cover?</p>
  <table class="tbl">
    <tr><th>KYB check</th><th>Why it matters</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Legal entity & ownership</td><td>Who ultimately controls this business? Verify UBOs (anyone owning 25%+)</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Business model</td><td>What are they selling? High-risk categories need specialist acquirers</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Financial health</td><td>Can they cover chargebacks if they receive many? Startups face higher scrutiny</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Processing history</td><td>What were their chargeback and fraud rates with previous processors?</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Website & terms</td><td>Clear refund policies, accurate product descriptions, visible contact information</td></tr>
  </table>
  <h3>High-risk merchant categories</h3>
  <p>Some business types are considered high-risk by default and may struggle to get standard acquiring:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Online gambling and gaming</li>
    <li>Adult content</li>
    <li>Cryptocurrency exchanges</li>
    <li>Pharmaceuticals and supplements</li>
    <li>Travel (high chargeback risk due to cancellations)</li>
    <li>Subscription businesses with free trials</li>
  </ul>
  <div class="box insight">
    <span class="box-icon">💡</span>
    <div>
      <div class="box-title">The rolling reserve — a buffer against chargebacks</div>
      <div class="box-text">New or higher-risk merchants are often required to maintain a rolling reserve — the acquirer withholds a percentage of settlements (typically 5–15%) for 90–180 days. If chargebacks arrive, the acquirer deducts from this reserve rather than chasing the merchant. For a growing business, this can be a significant working capital constraint — £10k/month in sales might mean £1,000 held back each month for 6 months.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="quiz" id="quiz-10-3">
    <div class="quiz-tag">✏️ Knowledge check</div>
    <div class="quiz-question" id="qq-10-3">A new travel agency wants to accept Visa payments. They're told they need a 10% rolling reserve for 180 days. Why?</div>
    <div class="quiz-opts" id="qo-10-3">
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('10-3',0,2)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">A</span>Travel agencies are required by law to hold reserves</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('10-3',1,2)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">B</span>The acquirer wants to invest the money during that period</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('10-3',2,2)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">C</span>Travel businesses have high chargeback risk (cancellations, flight changes) — the reserve protects the acquirer if chargebacks arrive after the merchant has been paid out</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('10-3',3,2)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">D</span>All new businesses have a 180-day reserve regardless of industry</button>
    </div>
    <div class="quiz-feedback" id="qfb-10-3"></div>
    <div class="quiz-footer"><span class="quiz-count" id="qc-10-3"></span><span class="quiz-score" id="qs-10-3"></span><button class="quiz-next" id="qn-10-3" onclick="nextQ('10-3')">Finish →</button></div>
