<!-- 11-1 -->
<div class="lesson" id="lesson-11-1">
  <div class="lesson-header">
    <div class="lesson-eyebrow" style="color:var(--gold)">Module 3 · Advanced · Chapter 11 · Lesson 25</div>
    <h2 class="lesson-title">Reading an ISO 8583 authorisation message</h2>
    <p class="lesson-lead">ISO 8583 is the messaging standard that underpins virtually every card transaction on earth. Understanding its structure is essential for anyone building or debugging payment systems.</p>
  </div>
  <h3>Message structure</h3>
  <p>An ISO 8583 message has four components: a <strong>Message Type Indicator (MTI)</strong>, a <strong>bitmap</strong> indicating which fields are present, and the <strong>data elements</strong> themselves.</p>
  <div class="box story">
    <span class="box-icon">📋</span>
    <div>
      <div class="box-title">Think of it like a standardised government form</div>
      <div class="box-text">The MTI is the form number. The bitmap is a checklist indicating which fields are filled in. The data elements are the actual answers. Every bank in the world uses the same form — they all know Field 2 is the card number, Field 4 is the amount, Field 39 is the response code. No ambiguity.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <h3>Message Type Indicators (MTIs)</h3>
  <table class="tbl">
    <tr><th>MTI</th><th>Message</th><th>Direction</th></tr>
    <tr><td>0100</td><td>Authorisation Request</td><td>Terminal → Issuer</td></tr>
    <tr><td>0110</td><td>Authorisation Response</td><td>Issuer → Terminal</td></tr>
    <tr><td>0200</td><td>Financial Request (debit auth — single message)</td><td>Terminal → Issuer</td></tr>
    <tr><td>0210</td><td>Financial Response</td><td>Issuer → Terminal</td></tr>
    <tr><td>0400</td><td>Reversal Request</td><td>Terminal → Issuer</td></tr>
    <tr><td>0420</td><td>Reversal Advice</td><td>Network → Issuer</td></tr>
  </table>
  <h3>Key data elements</h3>
  <table class="tbl">
    <tr><th>Field (DE)</th><th>Name</th><th>Example</th></tr>
    <tr><td>DE 2</td><td>Primary Account Number (PAN)</td><td>4532015112830366</td></tr>
    <tr><td>DE 4</td><td>Amount, Transaction</td><td>000000004999 → £49.99</td></tr>
    <tr><td>DE 11</td><td>STAN — System Trace Audit Number</td><td>123456 (unique per transaction)</td></tr>
    <tr><td>DE 22</td><td>POS Entry Mode</td><td>051=chip+PIN · 071=contactless · 010=magstripe</td></tr>
    <tr><td>DE 37</td><td>Retrieval Reference Number (RRN)</td><td>12-char unique ID for reconciliation</td></tr>
    <tr><td>DE 38</td><td>Authorisation Code</td><td>ABCD12 (only on approval)</td></tr>
    <tr><td>DE 39</td><td>Response Code</td><td>00=approved · 51=insufficient funds · 54=expired</td></tr>
    <tr><td>DE 41</td><td>Terminal ID</td><td>8-char terminal identifier</td></tr>
    <tr><td>DE 55</td><td>ICC Data (EMV TLV)</td><td>Contains ARQC cryptogram, ATC, TVR, IAD</td></tr>
  </table>
  <div class="box insight">
    <span class="box-icon">💡</span>
    <div>
      <div class="box-title">DE 55 is where EMV chip security lives</div>
      <div class="box-text">Field 55 (DE 55) carries the EMV chip data in TLV (Tag-Length-Value) format. This includes the ARQC (the unique cryptogram), the ATC (Application Transaction Counter — increments each transaction, catches replay attacks), TVR (Terminal Verification Results), and IAD (Issuer Application Data). When debugging chip transaction failures, DE 55 is always the first place to look.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="quiz" id="quiz-11-1">
    <div class="quiz-tag">✏️ Knowledge check</div>
    <div class="quiz-question" id="qq-11-1">A payment system returns an ISO 8583 message with MTI 0110 and DE 39 = "51". What does this mean?</div>
    <div class="quiz-opts" id="qo-11-1">
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('11-1',0,2)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">A</span>Authorisation request sent, approved</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('11-1',1,2)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">B</span>Transaction reversal approved</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('11-1',2,2)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">C</span>Authorisation response received — transaction declined due to insufficient funds</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('11-1',3,2)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">D</span>Financial request sent — debit successful</button>
    </div>
    <div class="quiz-feedback" id="qfb-11-1"></div>
    <div class="quiz-footer"><span class="quiz-count" id="qc-11-1"></span><span class="quiz-score" id="qs-11-1"></span><button class="quiz-next" id="qn-11-1" onclick="nextQ('11-1')">Next →</button></div>
  </div>
