<!-- 11-2 -->
<div class="lesson" id="lesson-11-2">
  <div class="lesson-header">
    <div class="lesson-eyebrow" style="color:var(--gold)">Module 3 · Advanced · Chapter 11 · Lesson 26</div>
    <h2 class="lesson-title">SMS vs DMS — two architectures for settling card payments</h2>
    <p class="lesson-lead">Not all card transactions settle the same way. Single Message System and Dual Message System are two fundamentally different approaches — and choosing the wrong one for your use case creates operational problems.</p>
  </div>
  <h3>Dual Message System (DMS) — the credit card model</h3>
  <p>DMS splits a transaction into two separate messages: an <strong>authorisation</strong> (0100/0110) and a separate <strong>clearing message</strong> sent hours later in a batch file. Funds are reserved at authorisation but only moved at clearing.</p>
  <p><strong>Used for:</strong> credit cards, signature debit, most e-commerce, hotel pre-authorisations, car rental hold amounts.</p>
  <p><strong>Key implication:</strong> the merchant must explicitly "capture" the transaction to trigger settlement. An auth without a subsequent capture expires (typically 7–30 days depending on scheme and MCC). Hotels and car rental companies routinely authorise more than the final amount — they adjust at capture.</p>
  <h3>Single Message System (SMS) — the debit card model</h3>
  <p>SMS combines authorisation and settlement into one message (0200/0210). Approval = settlement trigger. There's no capture step. Funds are debited in real time or near-real time.</p>
  <p><strong>Used for:</strong> PIN debit cards, ATM withdrawals, Maestro, some contactless debit transactions.</p>
  <table class="tbl">
    <tr><th></th><th>DMS</th><th>SMS</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Messages</td><td>2: auth + clearing</td><td>1: auth+settle combined</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Capture step</td><td>Required</td><td>Not applicable</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Partial capture</td><td>Supported</td><td>Not supported</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Reversal</td><td>Void before capture, refund after</td><td>Reversal (0420) sent quickly</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Common card type</td><td>Credit, signature debit</td><td>PIN debit, ATM</td></tr>
  </table>
  <div class="box warning">
    <span class="box-icon">⚠️</span>
    <div>
      <div class="box-title">Not capturing a DMS auth is a costly mistake</div>
      <div class="box-text">If your system authorises payments but fails to capture them (due to a bug, batch failure, or misconfiguration), customers are charged nothing — but the funds are reserved on their account as a pending charge, causing confusion. The authorisation expires eventually, but you've fulfilled the order without getting paid. Always monitor capture success rates.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="quiz" id="quiz-11-2">
    <div class="quiz-tag">✏️ Knowledge check</div>
    <div class="quiz-question" id="qq-11-2">A hotel pre-authorises a guest's credit card for £500 at check-in. At checkout the actual bill is £347. Using DMS, what should the hotel do?</div>
    <div class="quiz-opts" id="qo-11-2">
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('11-2',0,1)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">A</span>Charge the full £500 since that was authorised</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('11-2',1,1)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">B</span>Capture £347 (the actual amount) — the £500 auth allows any capture up to that amount; the remaining £153 hold is released</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('11-2',2,1)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">C</span>Issue a refund of £153 immediately after charging £500</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('11-2',3,1)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">D</span>The authorisation must be voided and a new one for £347 initiated</button>
    </div>
    <div class="quiz-feedback" id="qfb-11-2"></div>
    <div class="quiz-footer"><span class="quiz-count" id="qc-11-2"></span><span class="quiz-score" id="qs-11-2"></span><button class="quiz-next" id="qn-11-2" onclick="nextQ('11-2')">Next →</button></div>
  </div>
