<!-- 12-1 -->
<div class="lesson" id="lesson-12-1">
  <div class="lesson-header">
    <div class="lesson-eyebrow" style="color:var(--gold)">Module 3 · Advanced · Chapter 12 · Lesson 27</div>
    <h2 class="lesson-title">What happens inside a 3DS authentication request</h2>
    <p class="lesson-lead">3DS 2 is not just "send a text." It's a multi-party protocol involving structured JSON messages between five systems. Understanding the message flow is essential for integration and troubleshooting.</p>
  </div>
  <h3>The five participants</h3>
  <table class="tbl">
    <tr><th>Participant</th><th>Role</th><th>Who runs it</th></tr>
    <tr><td>3DS Requestor / Server</td><td>Initiates the 3DS flow on behalf of the merchant</td><td>Merchant or their PSP</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Directory Server (DS)</td><td>Routes auth requests to the correct ACS; holds 3DS configuration</td><td>Visa / Mastercard</td></tr>
    <tr><td>ACS (Access Control Server)</td><td>The issuer's system that performs the actual authentication decision</td><td>The cardholder's bank</td></tr>
    <tr><td>SDK (if mobile app)</td><td>Collects device data and renders challenge UI in-app</td><td>Merchant's app</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Browser (if web)</td><td>Runs the 3DS fingerprinting JavaScript, hosts challenge iframes</td><td>Cardholder's browser</td></tr>
  </table>
  <h3>The AReq/ARes flow</h3>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Device fingerprinting:</strong> 3DS JavaScript collects browser/device data silently (screen size, language, timezone, JS enabled, etc.)</li>
    <li><strong>AReq (Authentication Request):</strong> 3DS Server sends a structured JSON message to the DS, then forwarded to ACS. Contains: card number, transaction details, device fingerprint, merchant info, cardholder account history.</li>
    <li><strong>ACS risk decision:</strong> The issuer's ACS evaluates all AReq data and decides: frictionless approval, challenge required, or decline.</li>
    <li><strong>ARes (Authentication Response):</strong> ACS responds with the decision (Y=frictionless, C=challenge, N=no, U=unable to authenticate).</li>
    <li><strong>Challenge (if C):</strong> CReq/CRes messages exchange the challenge interaction (OTP entry, biometric, push notification).</li>
    <li><strong>RReq/RRes:</strong> Final results communication confirming the authentication outcome.</li>
    <li><strong>CAVV:</strong> On success, the ACS generates a Cardholder Authentication Verification Value — a cryptogram included in the subsequent authorisation to prove 3DS was completed.</li>
  </ol>
  <div class="box insight">
    <span class="box-icon">💡</span>
    <div>
      <div class="box-title">AReq data quality drives frictionless rate</div>
      <div class="box-text">The richer the data in the AReq, the more confidently the ACS can make a frictionless decision. Merchants who pass minimal data see lower frictionless rates and higher abandonment. Key fields: <code>acctInfo</code> (account age, transaction history), <code>shipAddressUsage</code>, <code>browserAcceptHeader</code>, <code>browserJavascriptEnabled</code>, and the full device fingerprint. Don't skip optional fields.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="quiz" id="quiz-12-1">
    <div class="quiz-tag">✏️ Knowledge check</div>
    <div class="quiz-question" id="qq-12-1">The ACS responds to an AReq with "C". What must happen next?</div>
    <div class="quiz-opts" id="qo-12-1">
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('12-1',0,1)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">A</span>The payment is declined — C means cancelled</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('12-1',1,1)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">B</span>A challenge must be presented to the cardholder — they need to verify their identity via OTP, biometric, or push notification</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('12-1',2,1)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">C</span>The merchant must contact the issuer by phone</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('12-1',3,1)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">D</span>The transaction proceeds frictionlessly — C means confirmed</button>
    </div>
