<!-- 13-1 -->
<div class="lesson" id="lesson-13-1">
  <div class="lesson-header">
    <div class="lesson-eyebrow" style="color:var(--gold)">Module 3 · Advanced · Chapter 13 · Lesson 29</div>
    <h2 class="lesson-title">VTS, MDES and the Token Service Providers</h2>
    <p class="lesson-lead">Network tokenisation is run by the card schemes themselves — Visa Token Service (VTS) and Mastercard Digital Enablement Service (MDES). Understanding what they do and how they differ is essential for wallet integrations.</p>
  </div>
  <h3>What Token Service Providers (TSPs) do</h3>
  <p>TSPs sit between the wallet/device and the issuer. They maintain a token vault — a database mapping DPANs (tokens) to real PANs (funding account numbers). They also manage the full token lifecycle: provisioning, suspension, resumption, and deletion.</p>
  <table class="tbl">
    <tr><th></th><th>Visa Token Service (VTS)</th><th>Mastercard MDES</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Token format</td><td>16-digit DPAN, same BIN prefix as real card</td><td>16-digit DPAN, may differ from real PAN BIN</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Contactless</td><td>Visa payWave</td><td>Mastercard PayPass / Contactless</td></tr>
    <tr><td>TRID — Apple Pay</td><td>40010030273</td><td>40010030273</td></tr>
    <tr><td>TRID — Google Pay</td><td>40010075001</td><td>40010075001</td></tr>
    <tr><td>TRID — Samsung Pay</td><td>40010062376</td><td>40010062376</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Issuer API</td><td>VTS Issuer Web Service</td><td>MDES Digital Enablement API</td></tr>
  </table>
  <h3>Token states</h3>
  <p>Tokens have a lifecycle with distinct states:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Inactive:</strong> Token created but not yet activated (provisioning in progress)</li>
    <li><strong>Active:</strong> Ready for use in transactions</li>
    <li><strong>Suspended:</strong> Temporarily unavailable — card reported lost/stolen, or flagged by fraud</li>
    <li><strong>Deactivated:</strong> Permanently inactive — card closed, device removed, cardholder request</li>
  </ul>
  <div class="box insight">
    <span class="box-icon">💡</span>
    <div>
      <div class="box-title">Replacing a card doesn't break Apple Pay</div>
      <div class="box-text">When a physical card expires or is replaced, the real PAN changes — but the DPAN (token) in your phone can remain active. The TSP updates the token vault mapping from old PAN to new PAN. This is why Apple Pay often continues working even after you get a replacement card before you've re-added it. This is called Account Updater.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="quiz" id="quiz-13-1">
    <div class="quiz-tag">✏️ Knowledge check</div>
    <div class="quiz-question" id="qq-13-1">A cardholder reports their physical card lost. What should happen to the DPAN tokens on their registered devices?</div>
    <div class="quiz-opts" id="qo-13-1">
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('13-1',0,1)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">A</span>Nothing — tokens are separate from physical cards and unaffected</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('13-1',1,1)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">B</span>The issuer suspends the tokens (and optionally deactivates them) — stolen physical card could indicate compromised PAN, so tokens are suspended as a precaution</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('13-1',2,1)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">C</span>Tokens are automatically deleted and must be re-provisioned</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('13-1',3,1)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">D</span>Visa/Mastercard automatically notify all merchants to reject those tokens</button>
    </div>
    <div class="quiz-feedback" id="qfb-13-1"></div>
    <div class="quiz-footer"><span class="quiz-count" id="qc-13-1"></span><span class="quiz-score" id="qs-13-1"></span><button class="quiz-next" id="qn-13-1" onclick="nextQ('13-1')">Next →</button></div>
