<!-- 13-2 -->
<div class="lesson" id="lesson-13-2">
  <div class="lesson-header">
    <div class="lesson-eyebrow" style="color:var(--gold)">Module 3 · Advanced · Chapter 13 · Lesson 30</div>
    <h2 class="lesson-title">Token provisioning — the six-step technical process</h2>
    <p class="lesson-lead">We covered the concept of adding a card to a wallet in the intermediate module. Here's the actual technical handshake — what each system sends and receives.</p>
  </div>
  <h3>The provisioning flow in detail</h3>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Enrolment request:</strong> The Token Requestor (Apple/Google) sends a provisioning request to the TSP including the PAN (encrypted), TRID, device data, and cardholder information.</li>
    <li><strong>PAN lookup and eligibility:</strong> TSP decrypts the PAN, identifies the issuer via BIN, and checks whether the card is eligible for tokenisation.</li>
    <li><strong>Issuer notification:</strong> TSP contacts the issuer via their API (VTS Issuer Web Service or MDES API) requesting approval to provision this card on this device.</li>
    <li><strong>Identity & Verification (ID&V):</strong> The issuer applies their ID&V method — typically a one-time code sent to the cardholder's registered mobile number, or a prompt in their banking app. Determines decisioning: green path (automatic approve), yellow path (ID&V required), red path (manual review).</li>
    <li><strong>Token generation:</strong> On issuer approval, TSP generates the DPAN and the initial set of cryptographic keys (LUK — Limited Use Keys) for the first transactions.</li>
    <li><strong>Token delivery:</strong> DPAN and keys are delivered securely to the device's Secure Element (SE) or to the cloud (for HCE — Host Card Emulation). Token status set to Active.</li>
  </ol>
  <div class="box story">
    <span class="box-icon">🔐</span>
    <div>
      <div class="box-title">Secure Element vs Host Card Emulation</div>
      <div class="box-text">SE (Secure Element) stores the token and keys in a tamper-resistant chip in the device — the same chip used for SIM cards. This is how Apple Pay works (Apple's Secure Enclave). HCE (Host Card Emulation) stores the keys in software in the cloud, downloading them to the device just before a transaction. More flexible but considered slightly less secure than SE. Google Pay initially used HCE.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="quiz" id="quiz-13-2">
    <div class="quiz-tag">✏️ Knowledge check</div>
    <div class="quiz-question" id="qq-13-2">During token provisioning, which party makes the final decision on whether to approve the token and generate the DPAN?</div>
    <div class="quiz-opts" id="qo-13-2">
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('13-2',0,1)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">A</span>Apple or Google — they control the wallet and make the decision</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('13-2',1,1)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">B</span>The card issuer (the cardholder's bank) — they must approve before any token is generated</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('13-2',2,1)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">C</span>Visa or Mastercard — they generate all tokens autonomously</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('13-2',3,1)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">D</span>The cardholder's mobile network provider</button>
    </div>
    <div class="quiz-feedback" id="qfb-13-2"></div>
    <div class="quiz-footer"><span class="quiz-count" id="qc-13-2"></span><span class="quiz-score" id="qs-13-2"></span><button class="quiz-next" id="qn-13-2" onclick="nextQ('13-2')">Next →</button></div>
  </div>
