<!-- 14-1 -->
<div class="lesson" id="lesson-14-1">
  <div class="lesson-header">
    <div class="lesson-eyebrow" style="color:var(--gold)">Module 3 · Advanced · Chapter 14 · Lesson 31</div>
    <h2 class="lesson-title">How machine learning detects fraud in milliseconds</h2>
    <p class="lesson-lead">Modern fraud detection has moved well beyond rule-based systems. ML models trained on billions of transactions can identify fraud patterns that no human analyst would ever formulate as a rule.</p>
  </div>
  <h3>What ML adds over rules</h3>
  <p>Rule-based systems (velocity checks, country mismatches) are fast and explainable, but they're reactive — you write rules based on fraud patterns you've already seen. ML models can identify <em>novel</em> patterns, combine dozens of features in non-linear ways, and adjust to evolving fraud tactics without manual updates.</p>
  <h3>Feature engineering — what the model actually uses</h3>
  <table class="tbl">
    <tr><th>Feature category</th><th>Examples</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Card-level features</td><td>Days since card issued, historical decline rate, average transaction amount, std dev of amounts</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Merchant features</td><td>MCC fraud rate, time since merchant onboarded, transaction count today</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Behavioural features</td><td>Typing speed on card number field, time on page before checkout, copy-paste detected</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Network features</td><td>How many cards used from this IP this hour, IP reputation score, ASN type (residential vs datacenter)</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Temporal features</td><td>Hour of day, day of week, days since last transaction, transaction velocity in last 1h/24h/7d</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Graph features</td><td>Shared devices across multiple cards, email address patterns, shipping address clustering</td></tr>
  </table>
  <div class="box insight">
    <span class="box-icon">💡</span>
    <div>
      <div class="box-title">Gradient boosted trees dominate production fraud models</div>
      <div class="box-text">Despite the buzz around neural networks, most production fraud models at large banks and processors use gradient boosted trees (XGBoost, LightGBM). They're fast at inference (sub-millisecond), handle tabular data well, are relatively interpretable, and are robust to missing features. Neural networks are used for sequential pattern recognition (transaction sequences, text analysis) but rarely as the sole production model.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="quiz" id="quiz-14-1">
    <div class="quiz-tag">✏️ Knowledge check</div>
    <div class="quiz-question" id="qq-14-1">A fraud model flags a transaction as high-risk even though no individual velocity rule would have triggered. What advantage of ML does this demonstrate?</div>
    <div class="quiz-opts" id="qo-14-1">
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('14-1',0,2)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">A</span>ML models are always more accurate than rule-based systems</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('14-1',1,2)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">B</span>ML is cheaper to run than rules engines</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('14-1',2,2)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">C</span>ML can identify non-obvious feature combinations that collectively signal fraud — patterns no single rule would catch</span></button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('14-1',3,2)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">D</span>ML can access customer data that rules engines cannot</button>
    </div>
    <div class="quiz-feedback" id="qfb-14-1"></div>
    <div class="quiz-footer"><span class="quiz-count" id="qc-14-1"></span><span class="quiz-score" id="qs-14-1"></span><button class="quiz-next" id="qn-14-1" onclick="nextQ('14-1')">Next →</button></div>
