<!-- 14-2 -->
<div class="lesson" id="lesson-14-2">
  <div class="lesson-header">
    <div class="lesson-eyebrow" style="color:var(--gold)">Module 3 · Advanced · Chapter 14 · Lesson 32</div>
    <h2 class="lesson-title">Real-time risk orchestration</h2>
    <p class="lesson-lead">A single risk score isn't enough. Production fraud systems orchestrate multiple models, rules engines, and external data sources in a pipeline that must complete in under 300ms — before the authorisation response is due.</p>
  </div>
  <h3>The orchestration pipeline</h3>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Pre-screening rules:</strong> Hard blocks run first — known bad IPs, blocked BINs, velocity hard limits. Sub-millisecond.</li>
    <li><strong>Feature extraction:</strong> Transaction data enriched with real-time lookups — device fingerprint database, IP intelligence, historical transaction aggregates from feature store.</li>
    <li><strong>Model ensemble:</strong> Multiple models run in parallel — gradient boosted tree, neural network for sequence patterns, and a rules engine — scores are combined (typically weighted average or stacking model).</li>
    <li><strong>Policy engine:</strong> Final score combined with business rules — amount thresholds, merchant-specific policies, customer segment overrides.</li>
    <li><strong>Decisioning:</strong> Approve / Step-up to 3DS / Decline — with reason code for downstream logging and chargeback defence.</li>
    <li><strong>Feedback loop:</strong> Transaction outcome (including future chargebacks) fed back into training data for model retraining.</li>
  </ol>
  <div class="box warning">
    <span class="box-icon">⚠️</span>
    <div>
      <div class="box-title">False positive rate matters as much as fraud detection rate</div>
      <div class="box-text">A fraud model that blocks 99% of fraud sounds excellent — but if it also blocks 5% of legitimate transactions, the business loses far more in declined revenue than it saves in prevented fraud. Optimising the trade-off between fraud rate and false positive rate (measured by the ROC curve) is the core challenge of production fraud modelling. Most teams track both the fraud rate and the false positive rate on a daily basis.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="quiz" id="quiz-14-2">
    <div class="quiz-tag">✏️ Knowledge check</div>
    <div class="quiz-question" id="qq-14-2">A fraud team tightens their model threshold from 0.7 to 0.5 (lower threshold = block more). What is the likely trade-off?</div>
    <div class="quiz-opts" id="qo-14-2">
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('14-2',0,1)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">A</span>Fraud detection improves with no downside</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('14-2',1,1)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">B</span>More fraud is blocked, but more legitimate transactions are also declined (higher false positive rate) — a revenue vs risk trade-off</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('14-2',2,1)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">C</span>The model runs faster because it blocks transactions earlier</button>
      <button class="quiz-opt" onclick="answer('14-2',3,1)"><span class="quiz-opt-letter">D</span>Interchange rates decrease because fewer fraudulent transactions complete</button>
    </div>
    <div class="quiz-feedback" id="qfb-14-2"></div>
    <div class="quiz-footer"><span class="quiz-count" id="qc-14-2"></span><span class="quiz-score" id="qs-14-2"></span><button class="quiz-next" id="qn-14-2" onclick="nextQ('14-2')">Next →</button></div>
  </div>
