<div class="lesson" id="lesson-15-1">
  <div class="lesson-header">
    <div class="lesson-eyebrow" style="color:var(--gold)">Module 3 · Advanced · Chapter 15 · Lesson 33</div>
    <h2 class="lesson-title">Scheme monitoring programmes — VDMP, VFMP, and ECP</h2>
    <p class="lesson-lead">Visa and Mastercard don't just set the rules — they actively monitor every merchant's fraud and chargeback rates. Exceeding thresholds triggers escalating fines. These programmes are the schemes' enforcement mechanism.</p>
  </div>
  <h3>Visa programmes</h3>
  <table class="tbl">
    <tr><th>Programme</th><th>Full name</th><th>Trigger</th><th>Consequence</th></tr>
    <tr><td>VDMP</td><td>Visa Dispute Monitoring Programme</td><td>Chargeback ratio ≥0.65% or count ≥75 in a month</td><td>Monthly fines from month 4; potential termination at month 12</td></tr>
    <tr><td>VFMP</td><td>Visa Fraud Monitoring Programme</td><td>Fraud-to-sales ratio ≥0.65% or fraud amount ≥$75k</td><td>Monthly fines; liability shift rules change</td></tr>
    <tr><td>High-Risk</td><td>High Risk VDMP</td><td>Ratio ≥1.8% or count ≥1,000</td><td>Immediate fines; faster termination timeline</td></tr>
  </table>
  <h3>Mastercard programmes</h3>
  <table class="tbl">
    <tr><th>Programme</th><th>Trigger</th><th>Consequence</th></tr>
    <tr><td>ECP (Excessive Chargeback Programme)</td><td>Chargeback ratio ≥1% and count ≥100</td><td>Fines of $1,000–$100,000/month depending on ratio and duration</td></tr>
    <tr><td>BRAM (Business Risk Assessment & Monitoring)</td><td>Elevated fraud or chargeback metrics</td><td>Additional monitoring; acquirer may require remediation plan</td></tr>
  </table>
  <div class="box warning">
    <span class="box-icon">⚠️</span>
    <div>
      <div class="box-title">Monitoring programmes are cumulative — the longer you're in them, the more expensive they get</div>
      <div class="box-text">Visa's VDMP starts fining at month 4 of being in the programme. Fines escalate each month you remain: $50 per excess chargeback in month 4–6, $25 per excess in month 7+, plus flat monthly fees. Being in a programme for a year can cost hundreds of thousands of dollars. Acquirers typically issue warnings long before fines reach critical levels — but ignoring those warnings is expensive.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
