<!-- 15-2 -->
<div class="lesson" id="lesson-15-2">
  <div class="lesson-header">
    <div class="lesson-eyebrow" style="color:var(--gold)">Module 3 · Advanced · Chapter 15 · Lesson 34</div>
    <h2 class="lesson-title">Compelling Evidence 3.0 — Visa's new tool for fighting friendly fraud</h2>
    <p class="lesson-lead">Friendly fraud — where legitimate cardholders dispute real transactions — accounts for an estimated 30–40% of all chargebacks. CE 3.0 is Visa's mechanism that lets merchants fight back using transaction history.</p>
  </div>
  <h3>What is Compelling Evidence 3.0?</h3>
  <p>Introduced by Visa in April 2023, CE 3.0 allows merchants to counter a Visa 10.4 (Card-Absent Fraud) chargeback by presenting evidence of prior, undisputed transactions from the same cardholder on the same device — proving the cardholder was known to the merchant before the disputed transaction.</p>
  <h3>The CE 3.0 requirements</h3>
  <p>To qualify, the merchant must provide evidence of at least <strong>two prior transactions</strong> that meet all of the following:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Completed between 120 and 365 days before the disputed transaction</li>
    <li>Were not themselves disputed as fraud</li>
    <li>Used the same device fingerprint (or same device ID) as the disputed transaction</li>
    <li>Used the same IP address as the disputed transaction</li>
    <li>The cardholder's account was created at the merchant at least 120 days before the dispute</li>
  </ul>
  <div class="box insight">
    <span class="box-icon">💡</span>
    <div>
      <div class="box-title">CE 3.0 makes device fingerprinting essential for e-commerce</div>
      <div class="box-text">CE 3.0 eligibility depends entirely on having stored the device fingerprint and IP address from prior transactions. Merchants who haven't been collecting and storing this data have no CE 3.0 defence available. This has made device fingerprinting and session data retention a compliance requirement, not just a fraud tool. Merchants need to retain this data for at least 13 months to cover the evidence window.</div>
